         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the measure [and] limit of ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">|| Just as ... is heard ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Wie man hört [bzw. man hört nämlich [folgendes] ], ... Gā- ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">As one [can] hear [OR: for one [can] hear [the following] ], ... Gā- ...</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>220</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (dia)dem as it were, ornament, decoration ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this one [is] the decoration [and] ornament of the (world). (In) the city Sudarśana ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... like the Vaijayanta [palace] of the ... g(ods). 1 || ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... through obtaining of ..., the Law ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the (foundations of the relics) have been put (in the stūpa). Therefore this monastery (is called) Dharmarājika ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (they obtained) bodies as the fruit of (deeds/merits). ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in (the palace) Badhe l(ike) god Brahman ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... this jewel 1 || If ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">Small fragment of the left side. The string hole space is preserved in lines 3 and 4. Lines a1 and b6 are lost. There are traces of signs in the margin of the recto side.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>·ñ(i)s</hi> is most likely a gen.sg. (or pl.?).</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">The phrase <hi>mäṃtne klyoṣtä(r)</hi> also attested in the small fragment <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht2166"/> a 2.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Probably, <hi>tont</hi> is the fem.nom.pl. PPt of <w lemmaRef="E_A_tā_G"/> 'to put'. For the name <hi>dharmarājika</hi>- lit. 'belonging to a king of the Law', see <bibl><title corresp="ref:edgerton1953"/><citedRange>281a</citedRange></bibl> and <bibl><title corresp="ref:swft1973"/></bibl> II: 530a; actually, it refers to a monument serving for the relics of the Buddha.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">One may restore either <hi>(pñintwā)śśi oko</hi> or <hi>(lyalypäntwā)śśi oko</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">The most likely restoration is <hi>(ṣtā)ṅkaṃ</hi> 'in the palace'. The personal name Badhe does not make sense, because there is no Sanskrit form <hi>badha</hi>-; it may stand for *Vadhe from Skt. <hi>vadha</hi>-, which would be a name by itself or a shorten form of a compound name; cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:edgerton1953"/><citedRange>397a</citedRange></bibl>. In theory, one may think of Skt. <hi>bādha</hi>- 'oppresser' <bibl><title corresp="ref:monierwilliams1899"/><citedRange>728a</citedRange></bibl>, but this noun does not make a proper name.</note></p>
         </div>
